    title: "Trichomoniasis",
    cellular: { title: "Pathophysiology of Trichomoniasis", content: "Trichomoniasis is the most common curable sexually transmitted infection worldwide, caused by the flagellated protozoan parasite Trichomonas vaginalis. The organism is an anaerobic, pear-shaped unicellular parasite with four anterior flagella and an undulating membrane that enable motility within the urogenital epithelium. T. vaginalis does not have a cyst form and is transmitted exclusively through sexual contact (vaginal intercourse). The parasite adheres to vaginal or urethral epithelial cells using surface adhesins and cytoplasmic projections, causing contact-dependent cytotoxicity through the release of proteolytic enzymes (cysteine proteases, cell-detaching factor) that damage the squamous epithelium. This produces a robust inflammatory response with neutrophil infiltration, mucosal microhemorrhages, and characteristic frothy, malodorous discharge. T. vaginalis infection alters the vaginal microbiome, elevating pH above 4.5 (normal 3.8-4.5) by disrupting Lactobacillus populations and consuming glycogen. The infection facilitates HIV acquisition by disrupting the mucosal barrier and recruiting HIV-target cells (CD4+ T-cells and macrophages) to the site of infection, increasing HIV transmission risk 2-3 fold. In women, infection involves the vagina, cervix, and urethra; in men, the urethra, prostate, and epididymis. While 70-85% of infected individuals are asymptomatic (especially males), untreated infection is associated with adverse pregnancy outcomes including preterm birth, premature rupture of membranes, and low birth weight." },
    riskFactors: ["Multiple sexual partners","Unprotected vaginal intercourse (condoms reduce but do not eliminate risk)","History of other STIs (co-infection with gonorrhea, chlamydia is common)","Female sex (women are symptomatic more often than men)","African American women have disproportionately higher prevalence rates","Older age among women (prevalence increases with age unlike bacterial STIs)","Non-use of barrier contraception"],
    diagnostics: ["Nucleic acid amplification test (NAAT): most sensitive (95-100%) and specific diagnostic method; FDA-approved for vaginal swabs, endocervical swabs, and urine in women; urine and urethral swabs in men","Wet mount microscopy: direct visualization of motile, flagellated trichomonads in vaginal secretions; specificity is high but sensitivity is only 51-65%; must be performed within 10 minutes of specimen collection (organisms lose motility)","Rapid antigen detection tests (point-of-care): OSOM Trichomonas Rapid Test; sensitivity 82-95%, specificity >97%; provides results in 10 minutes","Culture (InPouch TV or Diamond medium): considered previous gold standard before NAAT; sensitivity 75-96%; takes 2-7 days for results","Vaginal pH testing: elevated >4.5 in trichomoniasis (non-specific, also elevated in BV)","Pap smear: incidental finding of trichomonads; low sensitivity (60-70%); positive findings should be confirmed with NAAT before treatment"],
